In your last letter, dated the lst of March, you

long for a meeting between the two leaders, and have hopes of peace. But at the time of writing Ι fancy they will not meet, and that, if they do, Pompey will not agree to any terms. You seem to have no doubt as to what I ought to do, if the consuls go over—seas; well they will go, or rather have now gone. But bear in mind that of their number it is practically only Appius who has not a right to cross.
